out the distinctions and differences, revealing the difficulties that result when the research imperative is suffused with excessive zeal, adulterated by the profit motive, or used to justify cutting moral corners. Exploring the National Institutes of Health's annual budget, the inflated estimates of health care cost savings that result from research, the high prices charged by drug companies, the use and misuse of human subjects for medical testing, and the controversies surrounding human cloning and stem cell research, Callahan clarifies the fine line between doing good and doing harm in the name of medical progress. His work shows that medical research must be understood in light of other social and economic needs and how even the research imperative, dedicated to the highest human good, has its limits.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMedicinexResearchxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh  aamerican medicine.  aamerican society.  aannual budgets.  abioethics.  aboundaries of science.  acapitalist society.  acontroversial.  adrug companies.  aeconomic needs.  ahealth care costs.  ahealth care system.  ahealth researchers.  ahuman cloning.  ahuman subjects.  alimits of research.  amedical burdens.  amedical progress.  amedical research.  amedical testing.  amoral issues.  amorality.  apolitical history.  aprofit motives.  aresearch imperative.  asocial needs.  asociology.  astem cell research.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022771240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093923340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939233/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  Univ